{{Infobox court case | name = Morrison v Upper Hutt City Council | court = [[Court of Appeal of New Zealand]] | date_filed = | image = Coat of arms of New Zealand.svg | date decided = 18 February 1998 | full name = Morrison v Upper Hutt City Council | citations = [1998] 2 NZLR 331, [1998] NZRMA 224 | judges = [[Ivor Richardson|Richardson P]], [[Thomas Munro Gault|Gault J]], [[Andrew Tipping|Tipping J]] | prior actions = | subsequent actions = | opinions = | transcripts = | Keywords = negligence }}
'''Morrison v Upper Hutt City Council''' [1998] 2 NZLR 331, [1998] NZRMA 224 is a cited case in New Zealand regarding negilgence claims against the government .<ref name="McLay">{{cite book |title=Butterworths Student Companion Torts |edition=4th |last1=McLay |first1=Geoff |publisher=LexisNexis |ISBN=0-408-71686-X|year=2003 |page=}}</ref>
==Background== After first granting Morrison a building consent to build a new town house, the UHCC later withdrew the consent after discovering it had been issued outside of the District Plan.
Morrison appealed successfully to the Environment Court, and subsequently sought damages from the council.
==Held==
The court ruled that a council had no liability for making what is a quasi judicial decision.
